The paper deals with the knapsack problem, which is a classic problem in combinatorial optimization and falls under the category of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the computational complexity of the problem and its equivalence to the $(\min, +)$ convolution problem, which suggests that the paper could also be relevant to the discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and information theory (cs.IT) sub-categories. The paper proposes algorithms with near-linear running times, which could be of interest to researchers in computational geometry (cs.CG) and numerical analysis (cs.NA).
